<TEXT>
<P>
Morgan Creek Productions wants to corral all those "Young Guns" left standing 
after the climatic shoot-out for a sequel, currently titled "Hellbent for 
Leather." While Charlie Sheen, Dermot Mulroney and Casey Siemaszko's characters 
all died, negotiations are under way to sign survivors Lou Diamond Phillips, 
Emilio Estevez and Kiefer Sutherland. Since production is scheduled to get 
under way in January, when weather could be a problem, location scouting is 
going on in Arizona and Texas as well as New Mexico, where the original film 
was shot. . . Arnold Kopelson and Keith Barish will produce "The Fugitive," a 
$30-million film version of the 20-year-old TV series for Warners. Production 
is four to six months off as rewrites of David N. Twohy's script are being 
done. Sources indicate that British director Stephen Frears ("Dangerous 
Liaisons") and actor Harrison Ford are among those being approached about the 
project. . . . Meanwhile, Twohy is writing "Aliens III" for Fox. . . . 
</P>
<P>
Isabella Rossellini joins Bruce Willis in the caper film, "Hudson Hawk." 
Michael Lehman ("Heathers") directs the Joel Silver production for Tri-Star. 
The film rolls March 1. . . . 
</P>
<P>
William Hurt and Alec Baldwin have signed aboard Woody Allen's fall project for 
Orion. The film, which, as usual, is untitled, started filming last week. Woody 
has left himself out of the cast, but Mia Farrow is in. . . David Carradine 
stars as a preacher, and former porn star Tracy Lords plays the eldest of his 
five daughters in Eyefilm's "Prey, for the Wicked." Production on this dramatic 
thriller with religious overtones, written by John M. Bell and directed by Rick 
Eye, begins in January. Image will distribute. . . . 
</P>
<P>
Lewis B. Chesler, executive producer and creator of pay-TV's "The Hitchhiker," 
has purchased film rights to 1963 Japanese novel, "The Lady Killer" by Masako 
Togawa, a highly controversial and erotic thriller that dealt with role of 
women in that society. Screenwriter Robert J. Avrech ("Body Double") will adapt 
the book, and Carl Schenkel ("The Mighty Quinn") will direct. "Crimson 
Cabaret," the title of the film version, will film in Japan and possibly Hong 
Kong this spring. . . . KIRK HONEYCUTT 
</P>
