<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: BEGINNER'S PLUCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By John M. Wilson 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Marcia Dinneen concedes that she's a bit naive about the ways of the film 
industry. The Minneapolis writer -- currently working there as a shipping clerk 
-- only discovered that her original screenplay for "An Unremarkable Life" had 
started filming when star Patricia Neal called to chat -- six weeks into 
production. 
</P>
<P>
"She said, 'This is Patricia Neal -- I'm starring in your movie,' " recalled 
Dinneen, who added, "This is my very first attempt at writing a screenplay, so 
I'm learning the ropes. When it was sold, I just assumed it would automatically 
be produced." 
</P>
<P>
The recently released pic is about two small-town Pennsylvania sisters -- 
played by Neal and Shelley Winters -- whose self-protective routine is upset 
when a local auto mechanic (Mako) begins courting Neal's character. 
</P>
<P>
After selling her script to producer-director Amin Q. Chaudhri, Dinneen wasn't 
involved in revisions, and is vague about her reaction to the movie. She's just 
completed her second screenplay and is talking with L.A. agents. 
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people think it's a glamorous life," she said of her years of writing 
-- from articles to radio scripts. "They don't know how much work goes into 
it." John M. Wilson 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA111289-0022 </DOCNO>
