<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHITHER MAHLER? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Like columnist Herbert Glass, we too noticed that the Los Angeles Philharmonic 
is programming only one Mahler symphony this coming season (On the Record, Nov. 
5). 
</P>
<P>
Twenty-four years ago, a number of us Mahler fanatics marched good-naturedly at 
the Music Center, demanding more Mahler. Our group was born that night. 
</P>
<P>
Today, while America takes a Mahlerian respite, Europe is playing him wall to 
wall and Japan is worshiping at his shrine. 
</P>
<P>
As for Mr. Glass' complaint about Mahler being possibly out of favor, it could 
be time for us to dust off the old picket signs and show our displeasure in 
front of the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion. 
</P>
<P>
AVIK GILBOA 
</P>
<P>
President, Gustav Mahler 
</P>
<P>
Society, Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Los Angeles Philharmonicl 
