<HEADLINE>
<P>
WALL STREET / JOHN CRUDELE: EXPERTS ARE SURE THE DOW WILL EITHER RISE OR 
DECLINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE, JOHN CRUDELE is a financial columnist for the New York Post. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One guy on Wall Street thinks that the Dow Jones industrial average will fall 
8% more before the end of the year. Another agrees, but he's concerned that if 
the Federal Reserve doesn't continue to reduce interest rates, the stock market 
could go even lower. 
</P>
<P>
Sometimes you have to hit people on Wall Street over the head before they see 
the obvious. In this case, it took the investment community until last week to 
start realizing that corporate profits are becoming so weak that the stock 
market may be in for some bad time ahead. 
</P>
<P>
As I mentioned a few weeks ago, not everyone was oblivious to the 
corporate-profit trap. A minority in the investment community realized as early 
as this past summer that things weren't right in corporate America. But by and 
large, the vast majority of those on Wall Street thought that everything was 
hunky-dory -- until last week. 
</P>
<P>
Now, suddenly, most people who make their living peddling stocks are asking 
themselves one question: How low can it go? 
</P>
<P>
"I think the market is going to seek some level between 2,300 and 2,400 on the 
Dow over the next two or three weeks," says Anthony Woodruff, the head trader 
at Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. "I think the whole economy is slowing. There are 
recession fears," and, says Woodruff, there just isn't enough optimism to go 
around. 
</P>
<P>
Hugh Johnson, the chief investment officer for First Albany Corp., and one of 
the few who was warning investors in September, thinks that stocks will become 
attractive again when the Dow gets down to the 2,400 level. But Johnson isn't 
just worried about what is happening to corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
"It's not what's going on now that's the problem," says Johnson. "It's what 
lies ahead that's making everyone nervous." 
</P>
<P>
Fears were eased a bit last week when the Federal Reserve reduced interest 
rates, allowing the closely watched federal funds rate to drop to about 8.5%. 
</P>
<P>
Despite that action, a lot of people on Wall Street are still concerned. A 
slight reduction in interest rates is not enough to bolster the sagging 
economy. And a big drop in interest rates is unlikely while inflation is still 
a concern here and abroad. 
</P>
<P>
If the Dow were to drop to between 2,300 and 2,400, it would represent a loss 
of about one-tenth of its value. But if the decline comes suddenly, as it did 
Oct. 13, it could prove very damaging to the stock market's already-sagging 
confidence. And then there is no telling where the bottom will be. 
</P>
<P>
There are some people on Wall Street who see good things ahead for the stock 
market, if only short term. 
</P>
<P>
Richard McCabe, head of technical market analysis at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., 
for instance, thinks that stocks will go higher for the six weeks in the 
traditional year-end rally. 
</P>
<P>
But McCabe is anything but an optimist over the longer term. Says McCabe: "The 
Dow might yet make one new high. But we may then see more correction in 1990." 
McCabe says he wouldn't be surprised if stock prices dropped 20% to 25% during 
next year's first three quarters. 
</P>
<P>
John Connolly, chief investment strategist at Dean Witter Reynolds, is one of a 
very small group that thinks stocks are not vulnerable. "I don't think there is 
a great downside potential here," Connolly says of the market. Why? Because he 
thinks that the Fed -- despite persistent problems with inflation -- has 
already begun to come to the rescue of the economy by reducing interest rates 
and will continue to do so. 
</P>
<P>
Who's right? The majority isn't always wrong. I'd count on stocks slipping more 
than they rise in the months ahead -- even if there is a traditional December 
upturn. 
</P>
<P>
The "Rabbit" died. 
</P>
<P>
At least it appears that an attempt to raid Greyhound Corp. -- code-named 
"Rabbit" by the guy leading the charge -- won't occur soon. 
</P>
<P>
A Wall Street source says Daniel Good, an investment banker who made his mark 
as an adviser to corporate raiders while at Shearson Lehman Hutton, has been 
trying to line up partners for a run at the Phoenix-based company. 
</P>
<P>
But sources tell me that Good is having the same problem as everyone else -- 
raising financing for a takeover. In fact, his troubles appear to have stunned, 
if not killed, any plans that Good had for Greyhound. 
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing going on in this kind of market," says Good, who denied 
having any interest in Greyhound. Good added that he didn't think the takeover 
business would improve in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
Despite Good's denial, a reliable source on Wall Street tells me that Good has 
been making the rounds for the past few months carrying a data book on 
Greyhound, a company best known for the bus lines that it no longer owns. These 
days Greyhound makes an assortment of consumer products and runs a 
financial-services business. 
</P>
<P>
Greyhound has been a rumored takeover target for years. Good apparently 
believes that Greyhound is worth a lot more than its stock price, which last 
week was about $31. And Good has apparently even persuaded some investors to 
kick in a few bucks. 
</P>
<P>
But the banks are balking. And it's no wonder. Not everyone thinks as highly of 
Greyhound as Good does. An analyst at Drexel Burnham Lambert, for instance, has 
said publicly that he thinks Greyhound's stock is worth just $35 a share. 
</P>
<P>
Minneapolis investor Irwin Jacobs has been mentioned most often as a possible 
suitor. Jacobs, however, has sold his Greyhound shares. A source tells me that 
he dumped the last of his Greyhound stock earlier this year. So Jacobs won't be 
carrying this rabbit's foot around. 
</P>
<P>
An adviser to 250 retirement funds is telling his clients to get out of growth 
stocks now and into more conservative stocks with intrinsic values. And more 
important, he's telling them that by next February they should have only 25% of 
their money in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
Robert Moseson, president of Performance Analytics Inc., Chicago, says that 
growth stocks have done so well over the past year that they can't do much 
better. With the economy slowing, it's time for pension funds to start putting 
their money into more conservative stocks that have low price-to-earnings 
ratios and good income, he recently told clients. 
</P>
<P>
"People right now should move away from growth stocks -- like cellular 
telephone companies -- and toward higher-yielding stocks, like blue chips 
paying high-dividend yields," says Moseson. 
</P>
<P>
Moseson believes that different types of investment strategies take their turns 
in the limelight. And he thinks that the next strategy that will prosper is one 
that emphasizes higher-dividend, value stocks. 
</P>
<P>
When you think of people who have declared personal bankruptcy, you may 
envision down-on-their-luck losers destined for failure. But a new study by a 
group of professors shows that such a supposition is far from the truth. 
</P>
<P>
Elizabeth Warren, law professor at the University of Pennsylvania, says before 
her study of personal bankruptcy filings began, she assumed that a majority of 
the victims would be from one group -- an underclass of society. 
</P>
<P>
"Instead we found it was a cross section of the middle class of America," says 
Warren, whose co-authors are professors Jay Westbrook and Teresa Sullivan of 
the University of Texas. "We had accountants, dentists and entrepreneurs, as 
well as truck drivers." 
</P>
<P>
The professors studied 1,557 bankruptcy cases that were filed in Texas, 
Illinois and Pennsylvania. Warren said there was "no overwhelming reason" for 
bankruptcy filings except, generally, there was an "income interruption" 
because of illness or loss of job. "They can't keep up with their debt 
service," she added. 
</P>
<P>
But Warren said the blame can't be placed solely on borrowers. Lenders, she 
said, have been too willing to give loans to unqualified people. "The credit 
industry isn't being very careful," Warren adds, and doesn't shut off the 
spigot even when a borrower has debts wildly out of proportion to their income. 
</P>
<P>
Some other observations: 
</P>
<P>
* Medical debts aren't nearly as important in causing bankruptcy as had been 
thought. 
</P>
<P>
* Debtors in bankruptcy tend to have more kids -- an average of 3.4 to the 
normal 2.7. 
</P>
<P>
* Only about 45% of the wives work, compared to 60% in the general population. 
</P>
<P>
* One of five debtors in the study who filed for bankruptcy has operated his 
own small business. 
</P>
<P>
* And, nine of 10 who file for bankruptcy list some credit card debt. 
</P>
<P>
THE RUNOFF: The second deadline for making bids on Hilton Hotels Corp. is 
sometime this month, say Wall Street sources, who wouldn't be more specific. 
The sources say negotiations will begin after that, and a winner could be 
announced in December. There is still strong interest in Hilton, which put 
itself up for sale last summer, but some of the tire kickers have dropped out, 
the sources say. . . . 
</P>
<P>
John Sorte, co-head of investment banking at Drexel Burnham Lambert, says the 
leveraged buyout business is "very slow" right now, with deals "few and far 
between." Sorte says either borrowing costs paid by acquirers or acquisition 
prices have to come down to revive the business. . . . 
</P>
<P>
As I said a few weeks ago, there are still lots of corporate takeovers in the 
works. two weeks ago, it was Georgia-Pacific Corp. going after Great Northern 
Nekoosa. Wall Street sources say there's another small deal in the $500-million 
range coming soon and still another one twice that size is in the advanced 
stages of planning. Most of the deals are companies buying other companies -- 
sometimes in an unfriendly manner. Corporate raiders aren't very active . . . 
</P>
<P>
KPMG Peat Marwick, the accounting firm, says there is one portion of the 
takeovers business that is still doing well. Acquisitions of companies worth 
$100 million or less by foreigners -- cross-border acquisitions, KMPG calls 
them -- rose 22% in the second quarter, compared to a drop of 40% in deals 
worth $100 million or more. . . . 
</P>
<P>
Coniston Partners, the sometime corporate raider, has filed for a new 
partnership in Delaware that it's calling Condor. Coniston says it's just one 
of 20-odd partnerships that it has registered in that state. Wall Street's 
ever-imaginative speculators, however, think that the partnership may have 
something to do with Coniston's interest in making trouble for the management 
of UAL Corp. They figured this out, you see, because both condors and UAL's 
airplanes fly. Get the connection? 
</P>
</TEXT>
