<HEADLINE>
<P>
MISS MANNERS: A STORY -- YOU SUPPLY THE MORAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUDITH MARTIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seldom does retribution for a violation of etiquette come so swiftly. Miss 
Manners cannot resist telling you a story with a severe moral (although she 
will try to resist telling it gleefully): 
</P>
<P>
An old-fashioned lady was giving one of her old-fashioned dinner parties. 
</P>
<P>
Being of the old school, she had assembled her guest list not only for 
conversational compatibility, but so that the table would be surrounded by 
neatly alternating ladies and gentlemen. But on the day of the dinner, one of 
the guests called to say that she couldn't make it, but would stop in afterward 
for coffee. 
</P>
<P>
Not able to make it? As the hostess well knew, the only excuse for canceling 
out of a dinner party is sudden death. Lingering death won't do. 
</P>
<P>
This guest didn't sound dead at all. Her health was confirmed by the cheerful 
tone in which she explained that she had been invited to a fancy dinner given 
by someone quite important, and that she believed it would be useful to her 
career to go. She added that the gentleman with whom she lived -- and who had 
been invited -- would keep the original engagement, as he was not included in 
the later invitation. 
</P>
<P>
Now the hostess was so old-fashioned that she had no trouble whatsoever with 
unmarried couples living together -- she believed that this aspect of their 
life was none of her business. But to have someone frankly confess canceling a 
dinner date because a more advantageous opportunity arose shocked her into near 
immobility. 
</P>
<P>
She was strict enough, however, not to consider social catastrophe to be an 
excuse for letting down her guests. They could have survived without a full 
table, but this lady, the sort of perfectionist who measured the distance 
between place settings when setting the table, believed it her duty to fill in 
all the blanks. 
</P>
<P>
"Extra lady, extra lady," she thought desperately. "Whom do I know well enough 
to ask such a favor?" (She knew, of course, that while it is a compliment to a 
guest to issue an invitation at the proper time, it is an intimate favor to ask 
someone to come at the last minute. Proper reciprocation is not only a 
subsequent invitation, made far in advance, but the silent acknowledgement that 
the hostess must make every effort to be available for last-minute duty at that 
person's parties.) And then she thought of someone perfect -- someone who would 
not only even out the dinner table but grace it with beauty and wit. 
</P>
<P>
Indeed, that is what happened. And the party was a success. Even the gentleman 
who had been left behind, while his lady had moved up to something grander, 
seemed to be enjoying himself. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, he especially seemed to be enjoying himself. When the lady with whom 
he lived showed up as promised, for coffee -- prompting her hostess to believe 
that her coffee must be better than the other host's, for surely the social 
honor system could not have been a factor -- she found him sitting on a 
drawing-room sofa, next to the replacement guest. 
</P>
<P>
They were merely sipping coffee, chatting quietly and looking at each other, as 
proper guests do after a proper meal. The old-fashioned hostess thought their 
behavior impeccable. 
</P>
<P>
But the latecomer didn't. She took one look at them and understood immediately 
what had happened. As a desperate last-minute move to salvage her private life, 
she attempted to insert herself into the non-existent space between them. 
</P>
<P>
But it was too late. The gentleman escorted the latecomer home, and the other 
lady thanked her hostess, who pressed her hand warmly in a silent gesture of 
return thanks for saving the evening. 
</P>
<P>
Miss Manners is happy to report that some time after the dinner party, the 
gentleman and the so-called extra lady were married. This is a true story, and 
she invites her readers to supply the moral. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
